.TH HTYPE 1 "2025" "htype 0.2.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
htype \- mimic human typing on stdout
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B htype
.RB [ \-\-wpm
.IR N ]
.RB [ \-\-error\-rate
.IR F ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B htype
reads from stdin and writes to stdout one character at a time,
sleeping between each keystroke to simulate human typing speed.
Errors are injected randomly based on a QWERTY adjacency map and
immediately corrected with a backspace sequence.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BI \-\-wpm " N"
Typing speed in words per minute. One word is 5 characters.
Default is 120. Must be a positive integer.
.TP
.BI \-\-error\-rate " F"
Probability of a mistype on any given letter, from 0.0 to 1.0.
Default is 0.0. Errors are corrected immediately.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Echo a string at 80 wpm:
.RS
.EX
echo "hello world" | htype --wpm 80
.EE
.RE
.TP
Type a file with realistic errors:
.RS
.EX
cat essay.txt | htype --wpm 120 --error-rate 0.05
.EE
.RE
.TP
Chain with other tools:
.RS
.EX
cat script.txt | htype --wpm 100 | tee output.txt
.EE
.RE
.SH NOTES
Output is pipe\-friendly. The error correction sequence is
\fBwrong_char\fR, \fB\\b \\b\fR, \fBcorrect_char\fR \(em one keystroke
delay at each step.
.SH BUGS
Report bugs at https://github.com/lord-of-the-strings/htype
.SH AUTHOR
Written by Aadity Setu.
